\begin_layout Paragraph
DUO 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
a dual-class token structure that, combined with smart contract governed
 rules and market arbitrage mechanism, provides principal-guaranteed fixed
 incomes and leveraged capital gains for holders of each class.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Class A Token
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
also known as the Income Token, continuously accumulates interests based
 on its original net value at last Reset event.
 It will receive token payments at each Reset event.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Class B Token
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
also known as the Leverage Token, entitles leveraged participation of the
 underlying digital assets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Custodian smart contract performs multiple tasks that facilitate key
 mechanism of the system, including: creation and redemption of DUO tokens,
 safekeeping the underlying digital assets (e.g.
 ETH), calculation of tokens' net values, and execution of Reset events.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Creation and Redemption
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Creation-and-Redemption"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Creation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Dual-class tokens can be created by depositing underlying tokens to the
 Custodian contract.
 Upon receiving underlying tokens, the Custodian contract will return to
 the sender certain amount of Class A and Class B tokens.
 Such amount 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{B}$
\end_inset

 can be calculated by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
C_{B} & =\frac{M_{C}\cdot P_{0}\cdot\left(1-c\right)}{1+\alpha}\\
C_{A} & =C_{B}\cdot\alpha
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where, 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{C}$
\end_inset

 is the amount of underlying tokens sent to the Custodian contract,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is the processing fee of the smart contract,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is a positive number for determine the ratio of A and B
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $P_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the recorded price of underlying token in USD at last Reset event.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The deposited underlying tokens are kept by the Custodian contract, as collatera
l of the Class A and Class B tokens issued by the contract.
 Any user or member of the public can verify the collateral and tokens issued
 through third party applications such as 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Etherscan.io"
target "etherscan.io"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Redemption
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Holders of Class A and Class B tokens can withdraw deposited underlying
 tokens at any time by performing a redemption.
 To do this, the user will send certain amount of Class A and Class B tokens
 to the Custodian contract.
 The contract will deduct Class A and Class B tokens, and return return
 to the sender certain amount of underlying tokens.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The amount 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{B}$
\end_inset

 deducted by the contract is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
R & =\min\left\{ \frac{M_{A}}{\alpha},M_{B}\right\} \\
R_{A} & =R\cdot\alpha\\
R_{B} & =R
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where, 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{A}$
\end_inset

 is the amount of Class A sent to the Custodian contract,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $M_{B}$
\end_inset

 is the amount of Class B sent to the Custodian contract.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The amount 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{R}$
\end_inset

 returned by the contract is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{R}=\frac{R\cdot\left(1-c\right)\cdot\left(1+\alpha\right)}{P_{0}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Net Value
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The net value of tokens are calculated based on the coupon rate, the elapsed
 time from last Reset event, and the latest underlying token price in USD
 fed to the system.
 In particular:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
V_{A}^{t} & =1+r\cdot t\\
V_{B}^{t} & =\left(1+\alpha\right)\cdot\frac{P_{t}}{P_{0}}-\alpha\cdot V_{A}^{t}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where, 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is the daily coupon rate,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is the number of days from last Reset event,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $P_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the current price of underlying token in USD.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Quantity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Below holds in the system at all time
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Q_{A}^{t}=Q_{B}^{t}\cdot\alpha
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{A}^{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{B}^{t}$
\end_inset

 are the total amount of Class A and Class B tokens.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Implied Leverage Ratio
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
L_{B}^{t} & =\frac{P_{t}}{P_{0}}\cdot\frac{\left(1+\alpha\right)}{V_{B}^{t}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that at inception, above simply reduces to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L_{B}^{0}=1+\alpha
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Resets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Simply put, the holders of Class B tokens borrow capital from the holders
 of Class A tokens and invest in a volatile asset (i.e.
 ETH), which leads the Class B token to possess a continuum of leverage
 ratios.
 To reduce risk of both classes, a set of upward and downward reset clauses
 is imposed.
 Resets preserves total value in the system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Contingent Upward 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When underlying token price rises, the Class B token's leverage ratio reduces.
 An Upward Reset is triggered when the Net Value of Class B token reaches
 upper limit
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}_{B}$
\end_inset

.
 The reset will restore the leverage ratio to 
\begin_inset Formula $1+\alpha$
\end_inset

, and the Net Value of both classes to 1 USD.
 By increasing Class B's leverage ratio, the structure retains attraction
 to leverage-seeking users.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Upon Upward Reset, both classes' holders will receive certain amount of
 ETH from the Custodian contract.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The underlying token amount 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{A}$
\end_inset

 for each Class A token and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{B}$
\end_inset

 for each Class B token:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
U_{A} & =\frac{\left(V_{A}^{t-}-1\right)}{P_{t}}\\
U_{B} & =\frac{\left(V_{B}^{t-}-1\right)}{P_{t}}\\
V_{A}^{t+} & =V_{A}^{0}=1\\
V_{B}^{t+} & =V_{B}^{0}=1\\
Q_{B}^{t+} & =Q_{B}^{t-}\\
Q_{A}^{t+} & =Q_{A}^{t-}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Total value in the system is unchanged after reset:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
 & U_{A}\cdot P_{t}\cdot Q_{A}^{t-}+U_{B}\cdot P_{t}\cdot Q_{B}^{t-}+Q_{A}^{t+}\cdot V_{A}^{t+}+Q_{B}^{t+}\cdot V_{B}^{t+}\\
= & \left(V_{A}^{t-}-1\right)\cdot Q_{A}^{t-}+\left(V_{B}^{t-}-1\right)\cdot Q_{B}^{t-}+Q_{A}^{t-}\cdot1+Q_{B}^{t-}\cdot1\\
= & V_{A}^{t-}\cdot Q_{A}^{t-}+V_{B}^{t-}\cdot Q_{B}^{t-}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Contingent Downward
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When underlying token price falls, the Class B token's leverage ratio increases.
 A Downward Reset is triggered when the Net Value of Class B token reaches
 lower limit 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

.
 Similar to an Upward Reset, a Downward Reset restores the leverage ratio
 and Net Value of both classes.
 By reducing leverage ratio and restoring Net Value, the structure strengtherns
 principal protection to Class A holders.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Class A holder will receive certain amount of underlying token from the
 Custodian contract.
 Additionally, a Downward Reset will reduce the total supply of Class A
 and Class B tokens by roughly 
\begin_inset Formula $1-h$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The underlying token amount 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{A}$
\end_inset

 of each Class A token is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
D_{A} & =\frac{\left(V_{A}^{t-}-V_{B}^{t-}\right)}{P_{t}}\\
Q_{B}^{t+} & =Q_{B}^{t-}\cdot V_{B}^{t-}\\
Q_{A}^{t+} & =Q_{B}^{t+}\cdot\alpha\\
V_{A}^{t+} & =V_{A}^{0}=1\\
V_{B}^{t+} & =V_{B}^{0}=1
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Total value in the system is unchanged after reset:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
 & D_{A}\cdot P_{t}\cdot Q_{A}^{t-}+Q_{A}^{t+}\cdot V_{A}^{t+}+Q_{B}^{t+}\cdot V_{B}^{t+}\\
= & \left(V_{A}^{t-}-V_{B}^{t-}\right)\cdot Q_{A}^{t-}+Q_{B}^{t+}\cdot\alpha\cdot1+Q_{B}^{t+}\cdot1\\
= & V_{A}^{t-}\cdot Q_{A}^{t-}-V_{B}^{t-}\cdot Q_{B}^{t-}\cdot\alpha+Q_{B}^{t-}\cdot V_{B}^{t-}\cdot\alpha+Q_{B}^{t-}\cdot V_{B}^{t-}\\
= & V_{A}^{t-}\cdot Q_{A}^{t-}+V_{B}^{t-}\cdot Q_{B}^{t-}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note above used the fact 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{A}^{t-}=Q_{B}^{t-}\cdot\alpha$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Periodic
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When a given time period has passed from the last reset time, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{A}^{t-}$
\end_inset

 grows to upper limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}_{A}$
\end_inset

, a periodic reset is triggered to restore the leverage ratio and net value
 of both classes.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{B}^{t-}$
\end_inset

 is less than 1, reset will be the same as the Contingent Downward reset.
 Otherwise, reset will be the same as Contingent Upward reset.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Market Mechanism
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Premium and Discount
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Like all fixed income products, Class A is expected to trade on premium
 or at discount with respect to its net values, depending on market condition.
 When Class A trades on premium, that generally indicates market has a higher
 demand for fixed income and less for leverage and thus investor is actually
 paying extra for Class A.
 On the contrary, when Class A trades at discount, that generally means
 market has higher demand for leverage and less for fixed income and thus
 investor need to be given more incentives to buy and hold CLass A.
 Whether Class A trades on premium or at discount has less to do with market
 sentiment but more to do with cost of funding or required rate of return,
 as for all fixed income products.
 Class A reflects market cost of funding in its price premium or discount.
 As time draws closer to period resets or market level is approaching contigent
 resets, Claass A would trade close to its net value as that is what investors
 will receive after resets.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Arbitrage and Market Equilibrium
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By definition, DUO is equivalent to the underlying, ETH in this case.
 Thus, its price SHOULD be the same as ETH.
 On the other hand, DUO is not traded directly in the market but split as
 equal amounts of Class A and Class B.
 As discussed in previous section, Class A can trade on premium or at discount
 depending on market condition.
 The same applies for Class B as market fluctates.
 When the combined value of Class A and Class B does not equal ETH, arbitrage
 opportunity exists.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Arbitrage via Creation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When both Class A and Class B trades on premium, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Sell 1 unit of Class A and 1 unit of Class B and Buy 1 unit of underlying
 token
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Send 1 unit of underlying token to smart contract and receive 1 unit of
 Class A and 1 unit of Class B
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Arbitrage via Redemption
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When both Class A and Class B trades at discount, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Buy 1 unit of Class A and 1 unit of Class B and Sell 1 unit of underlying
 token
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Send 1 unit of Class A and 1 unit of Class B to smart contract and receive
 1 unit of underlying token
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Many other factors also determine whether above arbtrage strategy can be
 successfully exeucted, such as bid ask spread of all the 3 components,
 Creation and Redemption cost as mentioned in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Creation-and-Redemption"

\end_inset

, abilility to short sell the required components.
\end_layout

